Calendars with two levels of cycles:
after: Very commonly a calendar includes more than one type of cycle, or has both cyclic and acyclic elements.

Most calendars incorporate more complex cycles. For example, the vast majority of them track years, months, weeks and days. The seven day week is practically universal, though its use varies. It has run uninterrupted for millennia.[2]
